1146A 101st Legislative Session 1146
2026 South Dakota Legislature
House Bill 1146
AMENDME NT 1146A
FOR THE INTRODUCED BILL
Introduced by: Representative Rehfeldt
1 An Act to adopt the physician assistant licensure compact.
2 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF SOUTH DAKOTA:
3 Section 1. That a NEW SECTION be added to a NEW CHAPTER in title 36:
4 PHYSICIAN ASSISTANT LICENSURE COMPACT
5 Section 1. Purpose
6 In order to strengthen access to Medical Services, and in recognition of the
7 advances in the delivery of Medical Services, the Participating States of the PA Licensure
8 Compact have allied in common purpose to develop a comprehensive process that
9 complements the existing authority of State Licensing Boards to license and discipline Pas
10 and seeks to enhance the portability of a License to practice as a PA while safeguarding
11 the safety of patients. This Compact allows Medical Services to be provided by PAs, via
12 the mutual recognition of the Licensee’s Qualifying License by other Compact Participating
13 States. This Compact also adopts the prevailing standard for PA licensure and affirms that
14 the practice and delivery of Medical Services by the PA occurs where the patient is located
15 at the time of the patient encounter, and therefore requires the PA to be under the
16 jurisdiction of the State Licensing Board where the patient is located. State Licensing
17 Boards that participate in this Compact retain the jurisdiction to impose Adverse Action
18 against a Compact Privilege in that State issued to a PA through the procedures of this
19 Compact. The PA Licensure Compact will alleviate burdens for military families by allowing
20 active-duty military personnel and their spouses to obtain a Compact Privilege based on
21 having an unrestricted License in good standing from a Participating State.
22 Section 2. Definitions
23 In this Compact:
24 A. "Adverse Action" means any administrative, civil, equitable, or criminal action
25 permitted by a State’s laws which is imposed by a Licensing Board or other
26 authority against a PA License or License application or Compact Privilege such as
Underscores indicate new language.
Overstrikes indicate deleted language.

1146A 2 1146
1 License denial, censure, revocation, suspension, probation, monitoring of the
2 Licensee, or restriction on the Licensee’s practice.
3 B. "Compact Privilege" means the authorization granted by a Remote State to allow
4 a Licensee from another Participating State to practice as a PA to provide Medical
5 Services and other licensed activity to a patient located in the Remote State under
6 the Remote State’s laws and regulations.
7 C. "Conviction" means a finding by a court that an individual is guilty of a felony or
8 misdemeanor offense through adjudication or entry of a plea of guilt or no contest
9 to the charge by the offender.
10 D. "Criminal Background Check" means the submission of fingerprints or other
11 biometric-based information for a License applicant for the purpose of obtaining
12 that applicant’s criminal history record information, as defined in 28 C.F.R.
13 § 20.3(d), from the State’s criminal history record repository as defined in 28
14 C.F.R. § 20.3(f).
15 E. "Data System" means the repository of information about Licensees, including but
16 not limited to License status and Adverse Actions, which is created and
17 administered under the terms of this Compact.
18 F. "Executive Committee" means a group of directors and ex-officio individuals
19 elected or appointed pursuant to Section 7.F.2.
20 G. "Impaired Practitioner" means a PA whose practice is adversely affected by health-
21 related condition(s) that impact the PA's ability to practice.
22 H. "Investigative Information" means information, records, or documents received or
23 generated by a Licensing Board pursuant to an investigation.
24 I. "Jurisprudence Requirement" means the assessment of an individual’s knowledge
25 of the laws and Rules governing the practice of a PA in a State.
26 J. "License" means current authorization by a State, other than authorization
27 pursuant to a Compact Privilege, for a PA to provide Medical Services, which would
28 be unlawful without current authorization.
29 K. "Licensee" means an individual who holds a License from a State to provide Medical
30 Services as a PA.
31 L. "Licensing Board" means any State entity authorized to license and otherwise
32 regulate PAs.
33 M. "Medical Services" means health care services provided for the diagnosis,
34 prevention, treatment, cure, or relief of a health condition, injury, or disease, as
35 defined by a State’s laws and regulations.
Underscores indicate new language.
Overstrikes indicate deleted language.

1146A 3 1146
1 N. "Model Compact" means the model for the PA Licensure Compact on file with The
2 Council of State Governments or other entity as designated by the Commission.
3 O. "Participating State" means a State that has enacted this Compact.
4 P. "PA" means an individual who is licensed as a physician assistant in a State. For
5 purposes of this Compact, any other title or status adopted by a State to replace
6 the term "physician assistant" shall be deemed synonymous with "physician
7 assistant" and shall confer the same rights and responsibilities to the Licensee
8 under the provisions of this Compact at the time of its enactment.
9 Q. "PA Licensure Compact Commission" "Compact Commission," or "Commission"
10 mean the national administrative body created pursuant to Section 7.A of this
11 Compact.
12 R. "Qualifying License" means an unrestricted License issued by a Participating State
13 to provide Medical Services as a PA.
14 S. "Remote State" means a Participating State where a Licensee who is not licensed
15 as a PA is exercising or seeking to exercise the Compact Privilege.
16 T. "Rule" means a regulation promulgated by an entity that has the force and effect
17 of law.
18 U. "Significant Investigative Information" means Investigative Information that a
19 Licensing Board, after an inquiry or investigation that includes notification and an
20 opportunity for the PA to respond if required by State law, has reason to believe is
21 not groundless and, if proven true, would indicate more than a minor infraction.
22 V. "State" means any state, commonwealth, district, or territory of the United States.
23 Section 3. State Participation in this Compact
24 A. To participate in this Compact, a Participating State shall:
25 1. License PAs.
26 2. Participate in the Compact Commission’s Data System.
27 3. Have a mechanism in place for receiving and investigating complaints
28 against Licensees and License applicants.
29 4. Notify the Commission, in compliance with the terms of this Compact and
30 Commission Rules, of any Adverse Action against a Licensee or License
31 applicant and the existence of Significant Investigative Information
32 regarding a Licensee or License applicant.
33 5. Fully implement a Criminal Background Check requirement, within a time
34 frame established by Commission Rule, by its Licensing Board receiving the
Underscores indicate new language.
Overstrikes indicate deleted language.

1146A 4 1146
1 results of a Criminal Background Check and reporting to the Commission
2 whether the License applicant has been granted a License.
3 6. Comply with the Rules of the Compact Commission.
4 7. Utilize passage of a recognized national exam such as the NCCPA PANCE as
5 a requirement for PA licensure.
6 8. Grant the Compact Privilege to a holder of a Qualifying License in a
7 Participating State.
8 B. Nothing in this Compact prohibits a Participating State from charging a fee for
9 granting the Compact Privilege.
10 Section 4. Compact Privilege
11 A. To exercise the Compact Privilege, a Licensee must:
12 1. Have graduated from a PA program accredited by the Accreditation Review
13 Commission on Education for the Physician Assistant, Inc. or other
14 programs authorized by Commission Rule.
15 2. Hold current NCCPA certification.
16 3. Have no felony or misdemeanor conviction.
17 4. Have never had a controlled substance license, permit, or registration
18 suspended or revoked by a State or by the United States Drug Enforcement
19 Administration.
20 5. Have a unique identifier as determined by Commission Rule.
21 6. Hold a Qualifying License.
22 7. Have had no revocation of a License or limitation or restriction on any
23 License currently held due to an Adverse Action.
24 8. Notify the Compact Commission that the Licensee is seeking the Compact
25 Privilege in a Remote State.
26 9. Meet any Jurisprudence Requirement of a Remote State in which the
27 Licensee is seeking to practice under the Compact Privilege and pay any
28 fees applicable to satisfying the Jurisprudence Requirement.
29 10. Report to the Commission any Adverse Action taken by a non-participating
30 State within thirty days after the action is taken.
31 B. If a Licensee has had a limitation or restriction on a License or Compact Privilege
32 due to an Adverse Action, two years must have elapsed from the date on which
33 the License or Compact Privilege is no longer limited or restricted due to the
34 Adverse Action.
