3 Section 6. Adverse Actions
4 A. A Participating State in which a Licensee is licensed shall have exclusive power to
5 impose Adverse Action against the Qualifying License issued by that Participating
6 State.
7 B. In addition to the other powers conferred by State law, a Remote State shall have
8 the authority, in accordance with existing State due process law, to do all of the
9 following:
10 1. Take Adverse Action against a PA’s Compact Privilege within that State to
11 remove a Licensee’s Compact Privilege or take other action necessary under
12 applicable law to protect the health and safety of its citizens.
13 2. Issue subpoenas for both hearings and investigations that require the
14 attendance and testimony of witnesses as well as the production of
15 evidence. Subpoenas issued by a Licensing Board in a Participating State
16 for the attendance and testimony of witnesses or the production of evidence
17 from another Participating State shall be enforced in the latter State by any
18 court of competent jurisdiction, according to the practice and procedure of
19 that court applicable to subpoenas issued in proceedings pending before it.
20 The issuing authority shall pay any witness fees, travel expenses, mileage
21 and other fees required by the service statutes of the State in which the
22 witnesses or evidence are located.
23 3. Notwithstanding paragraph 2, subpoenas may not be issued by a
24 Participating State to gather evidence of conduct in another State that is
25 lawful in that other State for the purpose of taking Adverse Action against
26 a Licensee’s Compact Privilege or application for a Compact Privilege in that
27 Participating State.
28 4. Nothing in this Compact authorizes a Participating State to impose discipline
29 against a PA’s Compact Privilege or to deny an application for a Compact
30 Privilege in that Participating State for the individual’s otherwise lawful
31 practice in another State.
32 C. For purposes of taking Adverse Action, the Participating State which issued the
33 Qualifying License shall give the same priority and effect to reported conduct
34 received from any other Participating State as it would if the conduct had occurred
Underscores indicate new language.
Overstrikes indicate deleted language.

1146A 7 1146
1 within the Participating State which issued the Qualifying License. In so doing, that
2 Participating State shall apply its own State laws to determine appropriate action.
3 D. A Participating State, if otherwise permitted by State law, may recover from the
4 affected PA the costs of investigations and disposition of cases resulting from any
5 Adverse Action taken against that PA.
6 E. A Participating State may take Adverse Action based on the factual findings of a
7 Remote State, provided that the Participating State follows its own procedures for
8 taking the Adverse Action.
9 F. Joint Investigations
10 1. In addition to the authority granted to a Participating State by its respective
11 State PA laws and regulations or other applicable State law, any
12 Participating State may participate with other Participating States in joint
13 investigations of Licensees.
14 2. Participating States shall share any investigative, litigation, or compliance
15 materials in furtherance of any joint or individual investigation initiated
16 under this Compact.
17 G. If an Adverse Action is taken against a PA’s Qualifying License, the PA’s Compact
18 Privilege in all Remote States shall be deactivated until two years have elapsed
19 after all restrictions have been removed from the State License. All disciplinary
20 orders by the Participating State which issued the Qualifying License that impose
21 Adverse Action against a PA’s License shall include a Statement that the PA’s
22 Compact Privilege is deactivated in all Participating States during the pendency of
23 the order.
24 H. If any Participating State takes Adverse Action, it promptly shall notify the
25 administrator of the Data System.
26 Section 7. Establishment of the PA Licensure Compact Commission
27 A. The Participating States hereby create and establish a joint government agency
28 and national administrative body known as the PA Licensure Compact Commission.
29 The Commission is an instrumentality of the Compact States acting jointly and not
30 an instrumentality of any one State. The Commission shall come into existence on
31 or after the effective date of the Compact as set forth in Section 11.A.
32 B. Membership, Voting, and Meetings
33 1. Each Participating State shall have and be limited to one delegate selected
34 by that Participating State’s Licensing Board or, if the State has more than
